\deftab720 {\pard\nisusnos\ltrpar\pardirnatural\ql\nowidctlpar {\f1\fs20 November is upon us now. \u160 ?In Cincinnati, brightly colored leaves remain on the trees well into November; the feeling of October lingers. \u160 ?We half-delude ourselves; maybe this year will be different, maybe winter won't come. \u160 ?But November has finally set in, even here in \u160 ?Ohio's southernmost (and most Southern) city.\par
\par
My Trio #3 for clarinet, cello and piano is subtitled "Shadows of November." \u160 ?The subtitle sounds better in French: "Les Ombres de Novembre." That's how it appears on the score's cover page because\u160 ?I wrote it for a superb French clarinetist, my good friend Lucien Aubert, and the trio in which he played, who called themselves "les Gavottes."\par
\par
You're invited to listen to the final movement, 3.5 minutes long, as recorded by les Gavottes. Gosh, they're good! \u160 ?You're going to love this, I predict.\par
\par
It might not sound November-ish, so let me explain. \u160 ?There are three movements in this work.  The first movement is ambiguous, like a November fog. \u160 ?The second movement is deeply mournful, perhaps the saddest music I've written. \u160 ?Then comes the {\f2\i third} movement, the one I want to share with you this evening.\par
\par
To me, this music expresses the bracing,\u160 ?exuberant, almost vulgar zest\u160 ?of November. \u160 ?We hunker down, snuggle into a cozy chair, stretch our legs in front of the fire, drink red wine, tell funny stories and laugh with our friends even as, outside, the freezing rain is slicing through the evening air. \u160 ?Half way through this movement the music becomes so spirited that it almost sounds like a high school band determinedly performing a half-time show in a heavy, pebble-y hail of sleet. \u160 ?\par
\par
This music is jovial yet biting, as if to say:\u160 ? the great god Pan never dies, the energy of life is forever reaffirmed. \u160 ?Which reminds me of a poem I wrote.\par
\par
I've written five books, but very little poetry. \u160 ?A few years ago, however, circumstances forced me to devise some words for a November-ish tune of mine which I wanted to include in a choral work. \u160 ?Choristers need words to sing, so I was forced to become, for once, a lyricist as well as a composer. \u160 ?I set myself to the task, bore down, wouldn't quit until I'd come up with something suitable. \u160 ?\par
\par
I think the words I came up with express the same ideas about November that are expressed musically in this trio. \u160 ?\par
\par
Here's the poem, such as it is.\f3 \par
\f4 \par
\f0 Life's Oldest Song\f4 \par
\f0 \par
Gone now are the autumn leaves,\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0 to cold earth they have fled,\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0 and all of the trees seem dreary now\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0 that once were yellow and red.\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0 \par
Over us now cold winds are blowing,\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0 mourning the passing of fall,\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0 reminding us of the truth immutable:\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0 death comes to us all.\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0 \par
Such words we cannot gainsay.\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0 This truth to all is known,\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0 and we feel it most keenly this time of year,\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0 when autumn colors have flown.\u160 ?\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0 \par
Yet look again at field and forest,\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0 study the stubble and twig:\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0 a hint of color foretells a blossom\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0 will bloom forth from each sprig.\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0 \par
So friends, let us gather now\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0 and sing Life's Oldest Song,\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0 reminding ourselves to love that well\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0 which we must leave ere long,\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0 \par
Consoling one another's sorrows,\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0 raising our voices high,\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0 living life more fully though knowing\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0 that,\u160 ?like leaves, we must fly.\f4 \par
