Gifts are on many people's minds, this time of year. \u160 ?You may not think of it this way, but you are {\f5\i gifting me} by allowing me to share these musical messages with you. \u160 ?When artists know their work is engaging an audience, even a small one, It means so much that it feels like a gift. Thank you.\f6 \par
\f4 \par
This time I want to share {\f5\i two} pieces -- a short original Christmas carol (2:48) and a somewhat longer set of variations (7:25) on that same tune. \u160 ?\par
\par
Non-Christian friends and fans, please pardon the Christmas reference. \u160 ?It's not my intention to proselytize. \u160 ?What I want to share is the sweetness of the tune, for its own sake, the Christian content aside.\par
\par
The carol is sung by Jose Rubio, a wonderful baritone who used to live in the apartment right above ours, here on Milton Street in Cincinnati. \u160 ?It was a joy to hear him vocalizing upstairs! \u160 ?\par
\par
In this recording, Jose sings the carol with such warmth and feeling that I fancy I can {\f5\i hear} him smiling as he sings. \u160 ?And I love the way rolls his 'r's.\par
\par
As befits a carol, the tune is simple and doesn't vary through the four verses. \u160 ?Instead, it\rquote s the {\f5\i accompaniment}\u160 ?that differs for each verse: \u160 ?the piano is {\f5\i tone-painting} the ideas expressed in the lyrics. \u160 ?\par
\par
To see how this is done, follow the words as you listen:\par
\par
\f6 On Christmas morn the birds all wake and fly, cu-roo,\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f6 to seek the Child with wand'ring cry, cu-roo, cu-roo,\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f6 the thrush, the swallow, the bluebird small,\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f6 they gather round His cradle stall, cu-roo, cu-roo, cu-roo.\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f6 \par
The crow and jay their raucous cries do still, cu-roo,\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f6 to join the dove and whippoorwill, cu-roo, cu-roo,\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f6 the larks in exultation sing\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f6 to glorify their newborn King, cu-roo, cu-roo, cu-roo. \u160 ? \u160 ? \u160 ?\u160 ? \u160 ? \u160 ? \u160 ? \u160 ?\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f6 \par
On silent wings the wise-eye'd owls descend, cu-roo,\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f6 the falcon and the sweet brown wren, cu-roo, cu-roo,\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f6 with quail and pheasant by Mary's side\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f6 the folk of field and glen abide, cu-roo, cu-roo, cu-roo.\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f6 \par
The feather'd choir its cheerful an-thems raise, cu-roo,\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f6 to warm the frosty dawn with praise cu-roo, cu-roo,\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f6 and with the angel host above,\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f6 they greet the tiny Bird of Love, cu-roo, cu-roo.\par
\par
\f4 The tune for this carol came to me in a dream in the Fall of 1978. \u160 ?This has happened only three or four times. \u160 ?I woke up and wrote it down, quickly! \u160 ?I was afraid I'd forget it.\u160 ? I always thought the tune sounded like a Christmas carol; later I added appropriate words.\par
\f6 \par
\f4 In scoring the tune, I had the idea of including, in the piano part, quotations of one of the world\rquote s most famous melodies.  Several times and especially at the end, you'll hear the piano accompaniment quoting the opening of J.S. Bach's most famous tune, "Jesu, Joy of Man's Desiring." \par
\par
Bach\rquote s \ldblquote Jesu\rdblquote  tune is one of the greatest melodies ever conceived, ever-fresh, always a blessing. \u160 ?What gifts old Bach left for us! \u160 ?\par
