Did you ever listen to a painting? \u160 ?I have. \u160 ?For hours at a time. \u160 ?\par
\par
For eight and a half years, I worked two or three days a week as a security guard at the Cincinnati Art Museum, keeping watch over fabulous treasures displayed in large, echoing galleries. \u160 ?When there were no visitors, I sometimes amused myself by trying to imagine what a painting would sound like if its subject matter were to be conveyed {\f2\i musically}.\par
\par
That little mental puzzle resulted in my two three-movement "Impressionist Suites" for\u160 ?oboe, clarinet and bassoon, each movement conveying the imagery and brushwork of a major French Impressionist painter.\par
\par
The Cincinnati Art Museum has only one painting by Monet, but it's a doozie. \u160 ?He renders the sombre cliffs of his native Normandy in tones of deep, dark rust and sets them in a tossing, vibrant ocean of sapphire, indigo, emerald and mint, dashed with strokes of salmon, magenta and lavender, arched by clouds like sherbet in a pink-orange sky.\par
\par
How can a composer catch {\f2\i that} in music?\par
\par
By consulting his memory. \u160 ?Our understanding of music is shaped by our memories of all the music we have heard. \u160 ?When I ran a search through my memory for nautical-sounding music, my recollections were awash with half-remembered sea chanteys, fragments from "HMS Pinafore," "La Mer" and the stirring scores of many a swashbuckling pirate movie. \u160 ?\u160 ?\par
\par
I thought of the 'colors' of those three piquant instruments: \u160 ?oboe, clarinet and bassoon. \u160 ?I put those three instruments to work, playing a canon. \u160 ?You'll hear it right off in the low bassoon, then an octave higher in the clarinet, then yet another octave higher in the oboe ... and we're away! like a ship with\u160 ?sails bellying into the wind! I Into the tossing, dazzling, salt-tanged seascape Monet evoked so memorably.\par
\par
I wrote my two Impressionist Suites in 2000 for my friend Lucien Aubert, clarinetist in {\f2\i Le trio d\rquote anches Ozi}.\u160 ? Since these are Frenchmen playing for French audiences, I thought a suite about French Impressionist painters might please all concerned. \u160 ?And it has. \u160 ?This Monet movement will please you, too, hopefully.\par
