\f4 Happy Valentine's Day!\par
\par
My valentine to you is this little Romance from my suite entitled {\f5\i Ceremony for flute and cello }(2011). \u160 ?It's performed by Betty Braunstein and Josh Aerie, the musicians who requested that I write it. \u160 ?They wanted music they could play at weddings when there would be no piano available, the musical forces being only the two of them: \u160 ?a flutist and a cellist.\par
\par
Imagining what I fancied would be appropriate music for a wedding ceremony, I wrote a work in five short movements, which are entitled:\par
\par
\tab I. The Prelude\par
\tab II. The Processional\par
\tab III. The Ceremony: Romance\par
\tab IV. The Recessional\par
\tab V. The Postlude\par
\par
As you see, the Romance is the middle movement, to be played in the middle of the wedding. \u160 ?I know that it's not usual for music to be played {\f5\i during} the actual ceremony, during the exchanging of vows. \u160 ? But what if music {\f5\i were} to be played during that amazing moment when a couple publicly affirms their love and commitment, symbolized ceremonially with the rings?  What would be the right music for {\f5\i that} moment?\par
\par
The music would have to be tender, sweet, delicate, and romantic, yes -- but not overstated, please. \u160 ?Nothing like the soaring exultation of Tchaikovsky's {\f5\i Romeo and Juliet}\u160 ?or Max Steiner's great love theme from{\f5\i\u160 ?Now, Voyager\u160 ?}(as if I could even write such wonderful tunes ... I wish!)\par
\par
I tried to write something simple and sincere, perhaps quietly expressing my own love story, married to the same remarkable woman for 42 years and counting. \u160 ?\par
