For a good many, this winter is the most miserable in recent memory.\u160 ? We need something to make us smile.\u160 ?\par
\par
Let's make off to sunny ancient Greece and spend a little time with that lovable cuss, Diogenes!\par
\par
I offer you {\f5\i The Philosopher}, the first movement of a three-movement choral work entitled:\u160 ?\par
{\f5\i Philosophical Anecdotes}.\par
\par
I wrote this piece in 1979\u160 ?for the Kenyon College Choir.\u160 ? I thought about the students who would sing it. \u160 ?They study philosophy and classics; surely they'd like to sing something sublime, ancient, Greek. \u160 ?But\u160 ?Kenyon students also have a sense of the irony of their situation, pursuing the liberal arts in Gambier, Ohio, surrounded by cornfields.\par
\par
I remembered Diogenes, the great curmudgeon.\u160 ? An ancient Greek philosopher, yes, but a wag, a grump, a mocker of mundane values. \u160 ?I thought that irreverent settings of anecdotes about a guy like Diogenes might appeal to the students.\u160 ? It did! \u160 ?They sang the music with gusto!\par
\par
Three of Diogenes' exploits are recounted in the piece.\u160 ? The first movement, {\f5\i The Philosopher}, sets to music a prose account of the old grump\rquote s most celebrated moment, when he snubs Alexander the Great.\u160 ? The opening words of the story have a distinctive calypso rhythm. \u160 ?Recite them yourself:\u160 ? "The philosopher Diogenes lived in a tub!" \u160 ?Snap your fingers as you half-speak/half-sing those words. \u160 ?Accent the important syllables and, bingo, you've got the opening of my setting, and thus the mood for the whole piece, an improbable combination of ancient Athens and {\f5\i calypso} music!\par
\par
I love to write rounds.\u160 ? Choirs learn them quickly and easily.\u160 ? Singing a round, a choir can sound terrific after only a few minutes of rehearsal.\u160 ? My setting of those words about Diogenes just happened to make a couple of mighty fine rounds! \u160 ?You'll hear them sung first in unison, then in parts.\par
\par
The second movement recounts Diogenes' famous search, with a lantern, in broad daylight, for an honest man, the third his contemptuous quip upon visiting a country fair, "Lord, how many things there are in the world of which Diogenes hath no need!" \u160 ?Those movements are funny, too, but let's hear them for some other time.\par
\par
