The Harvard University Choir recorded a beautiful rendition of a piece I wrote for them called: \u160 ?\ldblquote An Appalachian Lord's Prayer.\rdblquote \par
\par
You are among the first to hear this piece! \u160 ?This recording is not on any CD. \u160 ?I can share, however, because there is such a thing as an mp3. \u160 ?What times we live in, when such things are possible!\par
\par
What makes it "An {\f5\i Appalachian} Lord's Prayer? \u160 ?The words and the melody. \u160 ?\par
\par
I adapted the traditional Lord's Prayer, adding some Appalachian imagery. \u160 ?Here is the text:\par
\par
\f0\tab Beloved God, beyond the mountains, hallowed be Thy name,\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0\tab Thy kin-dom come, Thy will be done on earth as it is in heaven.\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0\tab Give us this day our daily bread and forgive us our debts\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0\tab as we forgive our debtors\u160 ?and lead us not into temptation.\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0\tab Deliver us, we pray, from evil, for Thine is the kin-dom,\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0\tab the power of morning, the sunset glory, now and forever more. Amen.\u160 ?\f4 \par
\f0 \par
\f4 The music is not "Appalachian" in the sense of "Yahoo!" and/or \u160 ?"Yee-hah!" \u160 ?It's not Bluegrass. \par
\par
Instead, the tune recalls those beautiful pentatonic Southern folk hymns, such as "The Lone Wild Bird," My Shepherd Will Supply My Need" and "Jerusalem, My Happy Home."\par
