\par
- - - - - -\par
\par
\par
Today I'm thinking about heroes, what makes a hero, and how to express heroism musically.\par
\par
I've known some heroes. \u160 ?My father, Colonel Richard Sowash, US Army Reserves, was a decorated hero of WWII. \u160 ?My Piano Trio #5, "Eroica," written in 2000, is dedicated to his memory. \u160 ?\par
\par
My Scoutmaster, Frank Culp, was a hero to me and to many other young men who came through Troop 152 in Lexington, Ohio. \u160 ?\par
\par
My grandfather, John Hoff, whose influence was the most important in my life, about whom I wrote lovingly in my otherwise comical autobiography, {\f5\i The Boy Who Would Be Famous}, entertained and inspired me, as a boy, with splendid stories of heroes from American history.\par
\par
Fifteen years ago I wrote a book for older elementary school children entitled, "Heroes of Ohio: \u160 ?23 True Tales of Courage and Character," dedicated to that same grandfather. \u160 ? For that book, my definition of a hero was: \u160 ?someone who volunteers to do something challenging to help other people.  Simple!\par
\par
Expressing heroism musically is {\f5\i not} so simple. \u160 ?\par
\par
Composers have expressed heroism: \u160 ?Beethoven's {\f5\i Eroica} Symphony, Wagner's {\f5\i Gotterdammerung}, Strauss' {\f5\i Ein} {\f5\i Heldenleben}.\par
\par
But they lived long ago and far away and {\f5\i their} heroic music, great as it may be, feels remote, perhaps too lofty, as an expression of heroism in the "here and now" {\f5\i of our own time}.\par
\par
Too, those are {\f5\i orchestral} works. \u160 ?When I set out to express heroism, I was writing for just three instruments: \u160 ?violin, cello and piano. \u160 ?Quite a different thing! \u160 ?No brass, no timpani, no string and wind sections sawing and tooting, triple {\f5\i forte}.\par
\par
Most of the heroic music that genuinely moves me reached my ears via film scores for great Hollywood westerns like {\f5\i The Magnificent Seven, How The West Was Won, The Big Country. }Also the TV westerns I grew up watching: \u160 ?{\f5\i Wagon Train, Bonanza. \u160 ?}To me, {\f5\i that} is what the music of heroism sounds like.\par
\par
Yet not exactly, not entirely. \u160 ?After all, I am not a composer writing scores for Hollywood westerns. \u160 ?My peculiar career has been as far removed from Hollywood as it has been from Academe or the New York avant garde. \u160 ?My challenge was to find a way to incorporate the galloping excitement, the expansive textures and the sense of adventure found in the best western film scores into a work of serious, contemporary chamber music.\par
\par
The result is this {\f5\i Presto}, the final movement from my Piano Trio #5, "{\f5\i Eroica,}" in which a feeling of heroism is intended to prevail over the darker, troubled music of the earlier movements.\par
\par
Does this final movement sound "too Hollywood?" \u160 ?I don't think so. \u160 ?You'd never hear music like this in a western film score. \u160 ?Does it genuinely express heroism, in a way that transcends the Hollywood influences? \u160 ?See what you think.\par
