Mardi Gras! \u160 ?This coming Tuesday! \u160 ? My church, Mt. Auburn Presbyterian, will put on its annual Shrove Tuesday Pancake Supper and a certain composer you know is the {\f5\i chef de cuisine}! \u160 ?A team of flapjack flippers will serve up home-made cornmeal-buttermilk pancakes alongside the best sausage to be had in Cincinnati, a city famous for its sausage. \u160 ?What's more, a Dixieland band will have us stompin' and struttin', throughout the evening. \u160 ?We're expecting about 200 to attend. \u160 ?It's a blast and I wish you and all {\*\nisusscroll\nisusarea1\xoffset0\yoffset18 }
my other friends and fans could be there.\par
\par
One of the tunes the band will play, along with traditional New Orleans standards, will be a tune of mine, entitled "Beignets and Gelato." \u160 ?It's an homage to the Crescent City where we've enjoyed three week-long visits over the last four years. \u160 ?We do love it so! \u160 ?We long to return. Such a fun-loving, lovable city!\par
\par
I want you to hear my only foray into Dixieland -- in its original {\f5\i orchestral} setting.\par
\par
In 2011, the Heartland Symphony Orchestra (a spirited community orchestra serving Brainerd and Little Falls, Minnesota) commissioned me to write an orchestral suite in honor of the orchestra's 35th anniversary. \u160 ?I wrote a half-hour piece called {\f5\i North Country Suite} which they premiered in April of 2012. \u160 ?\par
\par
Since the Mississippi originates in northern Minnesota I decided to portray that great, vast, storied river in the suite's third movement, entitled "Father of Waters" -- that's what the word "Mississippi" once meant in a Native American language.\u160 ?\par
\par
The movement begins almost inaudibly; \u160 ?you won't hear much in the first few seconds.\par
\par
Then come tentative, trickling fragments of tunes, an evocation of the bubbling of springs and the coalescing of little streams and creeks, already with a few jazzy "Blue" notes. \u160 ?These come together in a broad, rolling theme with a distinctively American, Western feel and then, just when the movement seems to end (about three and a half minutes through), comes a surprise:\u160 ? the music goes\u160 ?{\f5\i Dixieland}! ... because, of course, the Mississippi culminates in "N'awlins!" \u160 ?\par
\par
The Dixieland music is familiar-sounding because I deliberately wrote it in a very familiar style -- but the tune is original, I assure you -- that's {\f5\i my} tune, "Beignets and Gelato."\par
\par
I even included a banjo part, hoping the orchestra could locate a banjo player. \u160 ? Sure enough, at the premiere, the concert mistress' banjo-playing father was featured, his first performance before a crowd, and looking very trim and handsome, in his tuxedo!\par
